# Step 1: Connection request copy
LINKEDIN_RULE_0=Connection requests have a 300-character limit. Structure: (a) One specific observation about them or their company — NOT "I came across your profile." (b) One sentence about why connecting makes sense. (c) No pitch, no ask, no CTA. The goal is acceptance, not a meeting. Example: "Hey [Name], saw your work at [Company] on [specific thing]. Running something similar in the AI marketing space — would be great to connect." Keep it casual. No formal language.

# Step 2: Multi-touch sequencing
LINKEDIN_RULE_1=LinkedIn is one channel in a multi-touch cadence. Typical pattern: Day 1 — email. Day 3 — LinkedIn connect. Day 5 — call. Day 7 — email follow-up. Day 10 — LinkedIn DM if connected. Never send a LinkedIn message AND an email on the same day. Space them out. (See also DUPLICATE_OUTREACH_RULE in .carl/global for hard 24-hour channel block.)

# Step 3: LinkedIn → Apollo handoff
LINKEDIN_RULE_2=When a LinkedIn connection responds positively: (a) Check if they exist in Apollo (apollo_contacts_search). If not, create them (apollo_contacts_create) with LinkedIn URL, name, title, company. (b) Update brain prospect note with LinkedIn interaction details. (c) If they agree to a call/demo, add to calendar and update brain note with #demo-booked tag.

# Step 4: Post-outreach logging
LINKEDIN_RULE_3=After any LinkedIn outreach, update the brain prospect note with: what was sent, when, their response (if any), and next step. This prevents duplicate outreach and keeps the brain current. Also log to Apollo Activities if possible.
